Round 1
[Patient] What foods can I eat to help manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Focus on fruits, vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins like chicken or fish.

Round 2
[Patient] Are there any specific foods I should avoid?
[Educator] Limit salt, processed foods, sugary drinks, and high-fat items like fried foods.

Round 3
[Patient] Can I still enjoy soul food while managing my heart failure?
[Educator] You can modify traditional soul food recipes by using healthier cooking methods and ingredients.

Round 4
[Patient] How can I make my meals more heart-healthy on a tight budget?
[Educator] Buy fresh produce in season, look for sales on lean proteins, and cook at home.

Round 5
[Patient] Should I be concerned about cholesterol in my diet?
[Educator] Limit saturated and trans fats found in items like red meat, butter, and processed foods.

Round 6
[Patient] Can I have dessert occasionally?
[Educator] Opt for fruit-based desserts or small portions of treats to satisfy cravings in moderation.

Round 7
[Patient] How can I make sure I'm getting enough nutrients in my meals?
[Educator] Aim for a variety of colorful fruits and vegetables, whole grains, and lean proteins.

Round 8
[Patient] Are there any beverages I should avoid?
[Educator] Limit sugary drinks like soda and fruit juices, and choose water or unsweetened beverages.

Round 9
[Patient] Can I still enjoy my favorite cultural dishes?
[Educator] Yes, you can modify recipes to be heart-healthy by using less salt, oil, and sugar.

Round 10
[Patient] What are some easy heart-healthy meal ideas I can try?
[Educator] Try grilled chicken with a side of quinoa and roasted vegetables, or a spinach salad with berries.